{{for|the American pediatrician|Charles M. Ginsburg}} {{Infobox person |name = Charles Ginsburg |birth_date = {{birth date|1920|07|27}} |birth_place = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], U.S. |death_date = {{death date and age|1992|04|09|1920|07|27}} |death_place= [[Eugene, Oregon]], U.S. |occupation = Engineer |alma_mater = [[San Jose State University]] |known_for=Developer of first [[videotape]] recorder }}
'''Charles Paulson Ginsburg''' (July 27, 1920 – April 9, 1992) was an American [[engineer]] and the leader of a research team at [[Ampex]] which developed one of the first practical [[videotape]] recorders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.labguysworld.com/VTR-People.htm|title=Group photo including Ginsburg and his team|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> ==Biography== Ginsburg was born on July 27, 1920 in [[San Francisco]], California. At age four, he was diagnosed with [[Diabetes mellitus type 1|type 1 diabetes]].<ref name=nap/> He attended [[Lowell High School (San Francisco)|Lowell High School]] in San Francisco.<ref name=nap/>
Ginsburg earned a [[bachelor's degree]] from [[San Jose State University]] in 1948. He worked as an engineer at AM-radio station [[KCBS (AM)|KQW]] (now KCBS). He joined Ampex in 1951, and remained there until his retirement in 1986, holding the title Vice President of Advanced Technology.<ref name="CEA">{{cite web | url=http://www.ce.org/Events/Awards/485.htm | publisher=Consumer Electronics Association | year=2000 | title=Charles Ginsburg | accessdate=2007-07-16 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709120311/http://www.ce.org/Events/Awards/485.htm | archivedate=2007-07-09 | df= }}</ref> The engineering team that helped created the videotape recorder while working for Ampex under his direction were Charles Andersen, [[Ray Dolby]], Shelby Henderson, Fred Pfost, and Alex Maxey.
Ginsburg was elected a member of the [[National Academy of Engineering]] in 1973, being cited for invention and pioneering development of video magnetic tape recording for instant playback.<ref name=nap>{{cite web|author=Hammar, Peter|url=http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=4779&page=85|title=Memorial Tribute: Charles Ginsburg|publisher=[[National Academies Press]]|location=Washington, D.C.|p=84|date=1994|accessdate=September 27, 2018|archiveurl=http://archive.is/uPJ6A|archivedate=September 28, 2018}}</ref>
He died on April 9, 1992 in [[Eugene, Oregon]] of [[pneumonia]].<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/17/us/charles-p-ginsburg-71-leader-in-developing-video-recording.html|date=April 17, 1992|author=Saxon, Wolfgang|accessdate=September 27, 2018|title=Charles P. Ginsburg, 71, Leader In Developing Video Recording}}</ref>
==Honors and Awards== *David Sarnoff Award of the [[Society of Motion Picture and Television Engineers]] (SMPTE) (1957), *Vladimir K. Zworykin Award of the [[Institute of Radio Engineers]] (1958),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ieee.org/portal/pages/about/awards/pr/zworkpr.html|title=List of IEEE Vladimir K. Zworykin Award recipients|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> *[[Valdemar Poulsen Gold Medal]] from the {{Interlanguage link multi|Danish Academy of Technical Sciences|da|3=Akademiet for de Tekniske Videnskaber}} (1960) *[[The Franklin Institute Awards|Howard N. Potts Medal]] from the [[Franklin Institute]] (1969) *[[John Scott Medal]] from the [[Philadelphia City Council|Corporation of the city of Philadelphia]] *Video Achievement Award from the former International Tape/Disc Association (1975) *Inducted into the [[National Inventors Hall of Fame]] (1990).<ref>[http://www.invent.org/hall_of_fame/66.html Short bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051123185730/http://www.invent.org/hall_of_fame/66.html |date=November 23, 2005 }}</ref> *Inducted into the [[Consumer Electronics Hall of Fame]] (2000).<ref name="CEA" />
