{{Infobox artist | bgcolour = | name = James Ward | image = James Ward by James Ward.jpg | image_size = 220px | caption = Self-portrait by James Ward, 1848. | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1769|10|23}} | birth_place = [[London]], [[England]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1859|11|17|1769|10|23|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Cheshunt]], [[Hertfordshire]] | nationality = [[England|English]] | field = Painting, Engraving | training = | movement = [[Landscape art|Landscapes]], [[Romanticism]] | works = | patrons = | influenced = | awards = [[Associate of the Royal Academy|Royal Academician]] (R.A.) | module = {{Infobox |child=yes | label1 =Influenced by | data1 =[[George Morland]], [[Peter Paul Rubens|Rubens]] }} }}
'''James Ward''' {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[Royal Academy|RA]]}} (23 October 1769 &ndash; 17 November 1859) was a painter, particularly of animals, and an engraver.
==Biography== [[File:James Ward - Self-Portrait - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Self portrait, 1830]] [[File:James Ward - Venus Rising from her Couch - Google Art Project.jpg|thumbnail|James Ward - Venus Rising from her Couch -]] Born in London, and younger brother of [[William Ward (engraver)|William Ward]] the engraver, James Ward was influenced by many people, but his career is conventionally divided into two periods: until 1803, his single greatest influence was his brother in law [[George Morland]]; from that time, it was [[Peter Paul Rubens|Rubens]]. From 1810 or so, Ward started to paint horses within landscapes; slightly later, he turned to very large-scale landscapes, of which ''Gordale Scar'' ([[Tate]], [[London]]), completed in 1814 or 1815 and depicting [[Gordale Scar]] ([[Yorkshire]]) as an example of the [[Sublime (philosophy)|sublime]], is considered his masterpiece and a masterpiece of [[England|English]] [[Romanticism|Romantic]] [[painting]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
[[File:James Ward - Gordale Scar (A View of Gordale, in the Manor of East Malham in Craven, Yorkshire, the Property of Lord Ribblesdale) - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''Gordale Scar'']] Ward devoted much of the period 1815-21 to the painting of a gigantic work titled ''[[Allegory of Waterloo]]'' (now lost); this neither was much praised nor brought in the revenue Ward had hoped for. The experience may have embittered him, and the deaths of his first wife and a daughter were among other tragedies. Like many artists of the time, Ward sought commissions from wealthy gentry of their favorite horses, their favorite hunting dogs or their children.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C78CAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA3&lpg=PA3&dq=%22cock-shooting%22+levett&source=bl&ots=X8GDyUdv_z&sig=ZFfopLXl5t2yR1D_f1aXDNYgPFo&hl=en&ei=LY-PSu-3C4TOsgP3sZwH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7#v=onepage&q=%22cock-shooting%22%20levett&f=false |title=The Sporting Magazine, or Monthly Calendar of the Transactions of The Turf and The Chase and Every Other Diversion Interesting to the Man of Pleasure Enterprise & Spirit, Vol. 19, New Series, Printed for J. Pittman, London, 1827 |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-04}}</ref>
One such family that Ward painted and drew repeatedly, and whom he counted among his friends, were the [[Levett]] family of [[Wychnor Hall|Wynchnor Park]], [[Staffordshire]]. One of Ward's best-known portraits was his ''Theophilus Levett hunting at Wychnor, Staffordshire'' of 1817.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06EFD9103DF933A05754C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=The New York Times, Grace Glueck, July 30, 2004 |publisher=New York Times |date=2004-07-30 |accessdate=2012-02-04}}</ref> Another was Ward's 1811 painting entitled ''The Reverend Thomas Levett and his favourite dogs, cock-shooting''. Ward also painted a group portrait of three Levett children — John, Theophilus and Frances Levett.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christies.com/LotFinder/lot_details.aspx?intObjectID=4020490 |title=Group Portrait of John, Theophilus and Frances Levett, James Ward, November 1811, Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-04}}</ref> (For the Levetts, see link to the Ward exhibit at the Yale Center for British Art.)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oxIEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA232&lpg=PA232&dq=%22theophilus+levett%22&source=web&ots=DCbobeeDc2&sig=k4RfM7v3YYOdWwCnqlfXevFthO4&hl=en#PPA232,M1 |title=Animal Painters of England from the Year 1650, Walter Gilbey, 1900 |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-04}}</ref>
==Family== <!-- [[File:Ward, James — Horse (painting).jpg|thumbnail|left|File:Ward, James — Horse (painting).jpg]] --> James was the son of James and Rachael Ward. He was first married to Mary Ann Ward (no known relation) in 1794 and after her death to Charlotte Fritche in 1827 (supposedly a relative of his first wife). James and Mary Ann Ward had several children including: #Matilda Louisa Ward, who married the artist John Jackson. #George Raphael Ward, b. 1798, d. 1879 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/n/i/s/Patrick-T-Nisbett/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0154.html |title=Patrick T Nisbett |publisher=Familytreemaker.genealogy.com |date=1996-08-15 |accessdate=2012-02-04}}</ref>
James Ward was the paternal grandfather of the painter [[Henrietta Ward]] and the great-grandfather of [[Leslie Ward]], the ''Vanity Fair'' caricaturist.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
In 1830, Ward moved to [[Cheshunt]] ([[Hertfordshire]]) with his second wife, but he continued to work, particularly on religious themes. A stroke in 1855 ended his work, and he died in poverty. He is buried at [[Kensal Green Cemetery]].<ref name=Paths>{{cite book|title=Paths of Glory|date=1997|publisher=Friends of Kensal Green Cemetery|page=103|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref>
==Style== [[File:The_Deer_Stealer_by_James_Ward.jpeg|thumb|left|The Deer Stealer]] James Ward was one of the outstanding artists of the day, his singular style and great skill set him above most of his contemporaries, markedly influencing the growth of British art. Regarded as one of the great animal painters of his time, James produced history paintings, portraits, landscapes and genre. He started off as an engraver, trained by William, who later engraved much of his work. The partnership of William and James Ward produced the best that English art had to offer, their great technical skill and artistry having led to images that reflect the grace and charm of the era. He was admitted for membership into the [[Royal Academy]] in 1811.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/30/arts/art-review-dashing-world-of-animals-as-regal-as-their-owners.html?pagewanted=all |title=Art Review: Dashing World of Animals as Regal as Their Owners, Grace Glueck, The New York Times, July 30, 2004 |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2004-07-30 |accessdate=2012-02-04}}</ref> [[File:An Overshot Mill in Wales (Aberdulais) - James Ward.jpg|thumb|[[An Overshot Mill in Aberdulais, Wales]], 1847]] [[File:James Ward - Marengo - WGA25437.jpg|thumb|''Marengo'' 1824 (Private collection)]] [[File:LevettChildren.jpg|thumb|upright|''The Levett Children''. John, Theophilus and Frances Levett, Wychnor, Staffordshire, November 1811]]
One of Ward's best-known paintings,''The Deer Stealer'', was commissioned in 1823 for the sum of 500 guineas by Ward's patron Theophilus Levett. When the work was finished, Levett pronounced himself delighted with the results, and consequently raised the remuneration to 600 guineas. Subsequently, Ward was said to have been offered 1,000 guineas for the painting by 'a nobleman,' which he declined. The painting now hangs at [[Tate]] in [[London]].<ref>[http://www.sothebys.com/app/live/lot/LotDetail.jsp?lot_id=159447975 A Great British Collection, sothebys.com]{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref>
