{{infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL | onlysourced=yes}}
'''Juan de Dios Cañedo''' (born in [[Guadalajara]], 18 January 1786; died in [[Mexico City]], 28 March 1850) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] statesman.

==Biography==
He received a good education and was admitted to the bar in 1809. He was elected a deputy to the [[Cortes Generales|Spanish Cortés]] in 1813, and soon became prominent as a parliamentary orator. While in [[Madrid]], he published a manifesto to the Spanish nation in defence of the colonial interests, which was eagerly read both in [[Spain]] and her American possessions.{{sfn|Wilson & Fiske|1900}}

On his return to Mexico in 1824, Cañedo took part in the debate relative to the [[1824 Constitution of Mexico|new republican constitution]]. He was several times deputy and senator, [[Secretary of Foreign Affairs (Mexico)|minister of foreign affairs]] under [[Guadalupe Victoria|Victoria]]'s administration, represented his country as plenipotentiary in [[Brazil]], [[Peru]], and [[Chile]], and was in charge of the foreign office and the [[Secretary of the Interior (Mexico)|department of the interior]] under [[Anastasio Bustamante|Bustamante]]. Afterward he went to [[Europe]], where he resided for some years, and had just returned to Mexico when he was killed by an unknown assassin.{{sfn|Wilson & Fiske|1900}}

